<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06115033 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06115033 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  AUTO; ACCIDENT; MULTIPLE; INJURY; VICTIM; ALAMEDA; COUNTY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A 22-year-old Pleasanton woman driving a Honda Prelude at speeds up to 60 mphalong Niles Canyon Road was seriously injured Tuesday following a head-oncollision at a bend in the road where three other accidents have occurredsince the beginning of the year.;    Traffic along the road, which connectsMission Boulevard and Interstate 680, was blocked for two hours after the 9:50a.m. crash, which happened near the Rancho Aguirre campground. The speed limitis 45 mph in the canyon but 30 mph at the curve.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  THREE INJURED IN HEAD-ON COLLISION AT CURVEIN NILES CANYON ROAD  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The driver of the Honda, Roxann Lynn White was trapped inside, and a toolwas used to extricate her from the car. A helicopter then took her to JohnMuir Hospital in Walnut Creek, where she was listed in serious condition.;   Both her passenger and the pickup driver were taken by ambulance to EdenHospital Medical Center. The passenger, Van Philip Fredricks, 19, of Hayward,was listed in serious condition. The driver, Michael William Arnold, 31, ofFremont suffered a broken arm and was treated at the Castro Valley hospitaland released.;    The drivers were wearing seat belts. Fredricks was not,police said.;    The last accident at the bend occurred two weeks ago and wassimilar to Tuesday's collision, traffic Officer Bret Hamlyn said.;    Despitethe recent accidents, Hamlyn said police do not consider the site particularlyhazardous. He said traffic accidents occur more frequently elsewhere,including at Fremont Boulevard and Mowry Avenue, where about three accidentsoccur each month.;    Hamlyn said Niles Canyon Road &quot;is well-posted, and allthe accidents have occurred because of driver error. Most of the peopledriving the road are familiar with it, and because they know it, they thinkthey can drive fast around it.&quot;;    No one had yet been cited in Tuesday'scollision, but the investigation is continuing.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SANDRA GONZALES, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910424  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  306  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday April 24, 199100115033,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>